# {{ project_name }} - Development Rules

## Core Principles

### 1. Code Quality Over Speed
- Write clean, idiomatic Go first
- Optimize only when a profiler says to
- Test thoroughly before committing

### 2. Consistency is Key
- Follow the existing package layout (`cmd/`, `internal/`)
- Match existing command patterns when adding new ones
- Let `gofmt` settle all formatting debates

### 3. Communication
{% if has_logging %}- Log important events at the right level (`slog.Info`, `slog.Error`, etc.)
{% endif %}
- Document changes in CHANGELOG.md
- Write clear commit messages
- Comment complex logic, not obvious logic

## Development Standards

### Package Size
- Keep packages focused on one responsibility
- Split a package when it accumulates unrelated concerns, not at an arbitrary line count
- `internal/` packages are private to this module by Go's own enforcement - don't try to make them importable elsewhere

### Code Quality Checklist

Before committing code, ensure:
- [ ] `gofmt -l .` reports no files (run `make fmt`)
{% if include_linting %}- [ ] `golangci-lint run ./...` passes (`make lint`)
{% endif %}
- [ ] `go vet ./...` is clean
{% if include_tests %}- [ ] Tests written for new behavior
- [ ] `go test ./...` passes (`make test`)
{% endif %}
- [ ] Exported identifiers have doc comments
- [ ] CHANGELOG.md updated with changes
- [ ] No `fmt.Println` debug statements left in command code (use logging or remove)

## Testing Requirements

{% if include_tests %}
### Unit Tests
- **Requirement:** exported functions with real logic should have tests
- **Location:** `<file>_test.go` next to the file under test (Go convention, not a separate `tests/` directory)
- **Focus:** command behavior via testable entry points (`Run`, `NewRootCmd().Execute()`, etc.) that accept `io.Writer`, not by capturing real stdout

### What to Test
- **Yes:** command output, flag parsing, config loading/defaults, error paths
- **No:** third-party library internals (Cobra/urfave-cli's own behavior is already tested upstream)
{% else %}
### Manual Testing
- Test all new commands manually before committing: `go run ./cmd <command>`
- Verify `--help` output stays accurate
- Check error messages are clear
{% endif %}

## Git Workflow

### Branching Strategy
- `main`: production-ready code
- `feature/*`: new features
- `fix/*`: bug fixes

### Commit Guidelines

**Format:**
```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>

<body>
```

**Types:** feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore

**Example:**
```
feat(cli): add config subcommand

Adds `{{ project_name | snake_case | replace('_', '-') }} config show` to print
the currently loaded configuration.
```

## Error Handling Rules

### Always Wrap Errors with Context
```go
// Good
if err != nil {
	return fmt.Errorf("loading config from %s: %w", path, err)
}

// Bad
if err != nil {
	return err  // caller has no idea where this came from
}
```

### User-Facing Errors
- Command errors should be short, actionable sentences (Cobra/urfave-cli print `RunE`/`Action` errors to stderr automatically)
{% if has_logging %}- Use logging for diagnostic detail; keep the returned error message itself terse
{% endif %}
- Never leak internal implementation details (file paths, stack traces) in user-facing error text unless `--verbose` is set

{% if has_logging %}
### Logging Requirements
- **debug:** detailed diagnostic information, only shown with `--verbose`
- **info:** normal operational messages
- **warn:** recoverable issues
- **error:** failures that need attention
{% endif %}

## Security Rules

### Never Commit
- API keys, tokens, or credentials
- Private keys or certificates

### Use Environment Variables for Secrets
```go
// Good
token := os.Getenv("{{ project_name | snake_case | upper }}_TOKEN")

// Bad
const token = "sk-abc123..."
```

### Validate All Input
- Validate file paths passed via flags (avoid unintended path traversal when writing files)
- Check argument counts/types before use (`cobra.ExactArgs`, manual checks in stdlib mode, etc.)

## Documentation Rules

### Required Documentation
- **Package doc comments:** one per package, on the primary file
- **Exported identifiers:** doc comments starting with the identifier's name
- **README.md:** keep install/usage instructions current
- **CHANGELOG.md:** document all user-facing changes

## Dependency Management

### Adding Dependencies
1. Must serve a clear purpose - prefer the standard library when it's sufficient
2. Run `go mod tidy` after adding an import so `go.mod`/`go.sum` stay accurate
3. Check the module's license and maintenance status before adopting it

### Version Pinning
`go.mod` pins exact versions automatically via `go.sum` checksums - there's no manual pinning step like in some other ecosystems. Use `go get module@version` to bump a dependency deliberately, then commit the updated `go.mod`/`go.sum` together.

## Code Review Checklist

### For Reviewers
- [ ] Code follows project conventions
- [ ] Errors are wrapped with useful context
{% if include_tests %}- [ ] Tests cover new behavior
{% endif %}
- [ ] No unhandled errors (`errcheck` should already catch most of these)
- [ ] Breaking CLI changes documented

### For Authors
- [ ] `make fmt`{% if include_linting %} && make lint{% endif %}{% if include_tests %} && make test{% endif %} all pass locally
- [ ] Self-reviewed the diff
- [ ] PR description explains the "why"

